image.altText: People walk past roadside stalls selling coca cola and sprite, on a dirt road

props.synopsis: Papua New Guinea is reeling from a bloody massacre in the Highlands province of Enga, and the bloodshed suggests an armoury of automatic weapons funnelled through powerful community leaders is fuelling the violence.

title.children: PNG police say tribesmen who killed dozens in Enga massacre had M16s, AR15s and shotguns

image.altText: two bottles of gin side by side

props.synopsis: You might not have noticed, but Australia's biggest liquor retailers are now selling vast numbers of their own private-label wine, beer and pre-mixes. It's leading to concerns about a further concentration of market power.

title.children: Major supermarket chain accused of 'deceptive' labelling on homebrand Tasmanian gin

image.altText: an outside view of a row of houses

props.synopsis: When it comes to housing, we're witnessing a shortage of supply while demand is ramping up from a huge lift in population, fuelled by incredibly generous tax breaks. It doesn't bode well for affordability, writes Ian Verrender.

title.children: How turbocharging a tax policy from a bygone era could result in the death of affordable housing

image.altText: Photorealistic concept art of a warship gliding through open seas.

props.synopsis: Labor reveals the cost of the massive Hunter-class frigate project has leapt from $45 billion to almost $65 billion, as it prepares to trim the program while unveiling other shipbuilding plans.

title.children: $20 billion funding 'hole' in troubled Hunter warships, Labor claims

image.altText: A number of illustrations of grocery items, like milk, apples, sausages, around two 'specials' signs 'half price' and '40% off'.

props.synopsis: Four Corners has spoken to insiders, experts, and the supermarket CEOs themselves to find out just how they operate. Here's what you need to know.

title.children: Specials, phantom brands, price matching: The shopping list of supermarket tactics you need to know about

image.altText: A scientist testing a pill-like substance.

props.synopsis: Synthetic drugs are circulating in Australia, increasing the risk of overdose and poisoning. Experts say more pill testing could help.

title.children: Drugs are getting more unpredictable in Australia. Is pill testing the answer?

image.altText: Tim Stannard stands in front of a lamp and picture in his loung room.

props.synopsis: Tim Stannard says he's had long COVID for four years and can no longer hold down a job. Experts say patients feel let down by the government's response to a parliamentary inquiry into long the disease, calling it a "missed opportunity".

title.children: Tim thought he had 'a little flu', but four years later he can no longer hold down a job

image.altText: Satellite images show Rafah's tent city

props.synopsis: The city was once a "safe zone" for displaced Gazans. Now new satellite images reveal the reality of those fleeing the conflict.

title.children: Satellite images of Rafah reveal the reality of more than 1 million people fleeing conflict

image.altText: people sit in chairs in a circle.

props.synopsis: The United States has proposed an alternative draft United Nations Security Council resolution calling for a temporary ceasefire in the Israel-Gaza war and opposing a major Israeli ground offensive in Rafah in southern Gaza.

title.children: US presents alternative UN resolution to prevent further escalation in Israel-Gaza war

image.altText: A sign on a fence says 'asbestos'.

props.synopsis: Asbestos, it seems, is everywhere around Sydney at the moment. 7.30 went to industry insiders to find out why. The answer according to someone else who owns a similar business is a "major let-down in processes".

title.children: ACT and Queensland now testing mulch for asbestos as contamination concerns spread

image.altText: The flags of China and the USA are being displayed on a smartphone, with an NVIDIA chip visible in the background.

props.synopsis: A vast technology gap that has eaten deeply into Australia's ability to determine its own path is now so vast, it has become impossible to bridge, writes Linton Besser.

title.children: The vast technology gap that will leave Australia unable to understand the tech we have to buy

image.altText: Close up of man holding uncut green gem the size of aa 50-cent piece

props.synopsis: While the sapphire rush of the 1890s is long gone, these modern gem hunters are still eager to strike it lucky and enjoy the colourful lifestyle of Queensland's Gemfields.

title.children: This whopping sapphire was unearthed in Qld. Meet the gem hunters vying to find more

image.altText: Collage of Australian acts George Alice & Peach PRC against the TikTok logo with a banned sign across it

props.synopsis: "What do small fish do?" Homegrown acts are raising questions (and finding loopholes) regarding Universal Music Group pulling their music from the world's biggest social media platform.

title.children: Universal's TikTok battle has muted Australian musicians. But they're finding ways around it

image.altText: Assange, seen here looking much younger, holds up the newspaper which reads massive leak of secret fules exposes true Afghan war

props.synopsis: WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange will face a last-ditch legal challenge this week to stop his extradition from Britain to the US, in what his wife has described as a matter of life or death.

title.children: Julian Assange is about to face his last fight for freedom. Here's how we got here

image.altText: Snowtown accomplice Mark Ray Haydon.

props.synopsis: South Australia's Parole Board will meet to consider an application by "bodies-in-the-barrels" accomplice Mark Ray Haydon for release into the community. It’s the culmination of an application which has been under consideration since 2021.

title.children: A man convicted of helping the Snowtown murderers is seeking early release on parole. Here's what's next

image.altText: A Sushi Hub store in central Sydney advertises for staff.

props.synopsis: Fewer employers plan to add staff compared with last year, but not many have plans for mass lay-offs either, leaving the jobs market in wait-and-see mode at the start of 2024.

title.children: Nearly two-thirds of employers are excluding job applicants based on certain personal characteristics

image.altText: A bird's eye view of unit blocks and apartments with the ocean in the background on a sunny day.

props.synopsis: Data from CoreLogic shows the price difference between houses and apartments has widened to a new record as land values rise, a limited number of freestanding houses are being listed to purchase, and people desire more living space.

title.children: The price gap between houses and apartments is at a record high. Does it mean units are undervalued?

image.altText: An artist rendering of a black hole inside a mass of fiery red and orange material.

props.synopsis: Australian National University researchers discover a black hole whose mass is roughly 17 billion times that of our Sun, and exists within the brightest currently known thing being continually powered in the universe.

title.children: Fastest-growing black hole that consumes mass of 'the Sun and all the planets combined' every day found

image.altText: Close up of Taylor Swift looking serious on stage in sparkly bodysuit

props.synopsis: Good luck getting a hotel in Sydney. Swift's Eras Tour has packed the Harbour City's hotels and driven up short-term rental costs as thousands descend on the city ahead of four concerts.

title.children: 'Pricing was just ridiculous': Fans fork out thousands on accommodation as Taylor Swift prepares for Sydney shows

image.altText: A male NFL player engages hugs girlfriend inside a stadium, with cheering fans, cameras and confetti surrounding them

props.synopsis: As Taylor Swift takes over Australia in her Eras Tour, her presence in the NFL has brought more girls and women into the game, but it hasn't changed the harsh reality of the culture in many men's professional sports, writes Kasey Symons.

title.children: How the Taylor Swift effect is changing sports fandom

image.altText: The ASX boards in Sydney

props.synopsis: The Australian share market is likely to start its day relatively flat, while global markets struggled to rise after the chances of early interest rate cuts receded. Follow live.

title.children: ASX to open steady, European stocks hit two-year high

BHP half-year profit slumps 86 per cent
Competition tribunal to decide on fate of ANZ-Suncorp merger

image.altText: Image shows a five-person panel on ABC's Q+A with host Patricia Karvelas

props.synopsis: Labor Senator Malarndirri McCarthy tells Q+A she would welcome drug and alcohol testing for parliamentarians in the wake of incidents involving Barnaby Joyce and Perin Davey.

title.children: 'I have no problems with it': Labor senator welcomes drug, alcohol testing in parliament

image.altText: Chelsea Roffey

props.synopsis: Trailblazing AFL umpire Chelsea Roffey says she once went to a camping store to buy pants because the league-issued uniform was a poor fit — and it's a common problem one study hopes to address.

title.children: 'I looked like the Michelin Man wearing it': Study shows women umpires feel uncomfortable with their provided uniforms

image.altText: Police commissioner Katarina Carroll addresses the media while dressed in uniform

props.synopsis: Katarina Carroll was appointed police commissioner in 2019 becoming the first woman to hold the role in Queensland after serving as the commissioner of the Queensland Fire and Emergency Service.

title.children: Questions surround Queensland Police commissioner's future after statement release

image.altText: A woman and man with their arms around each other.

props.synopsis: Evgenia Kara-Murza, the wife of jailed Russian opposition politician Vladimir Kara-Murza, has no doubts who was responsible for the death of Alexei Navalny.

title.children: Vladimir has survived two Novichok poisonings. His wife fears Putin's third assassination attempt is inevitable

image.altText: A woman with her hair in a bun sitting in front of a blue background.

props.synopsis: Yulia Navalnaya has accused the Russian president of killing her husband in a video she uploaded to social media.

title.children: Widow of Alexei Navalny blames Putin for husband's death, vows to keep fighting for freedom

image.altText: Two men wearing orange shirts and lifejackets test the water along the Darling River at Menindee.

props.synopsis: Tens of millions of native fish have perished along the Darling River over the past five years following a series of mass kills. In an attempt to mitigate future deaths the NSW government are trialling technology that pumps pure oxygen into the water.

title.children: Darling River oxygenation trial hopes to avoid future mass fish deaths like Menindee

image.altText: Zendaya, left, wears robotic couture and smizes with Anya, centre in a flowing white headpiece, and Chris, right, in a grey suit

props.synopsis: All the (Taylor Swift-free) entertainment news you might have missed now the Eras tour frenzy has abated, from Beyoncé talking the legacy of Black hair to Eminem's new Stan documentary.

title.children: We unpack Zendaya and Anya's Dune looks and try to understand this Hemsworth's Met Gala role

image.altText: A middle-aged white man kisses a 30-something white woman on the forehead will holding a play script.

props.synopsis: Did you know the term "gaslighting" is from a 1938 play? A new adaptation shines a light on how gaslighting plays out in modern Australia.

title.children: 'I thought it was all my fault': How being gaslit led this theatre director to take on a classic

image.altText: Christmas island red crab migration

props.synopsis: Authorities say "exceptionally dry" conditions have put a dampener on this season's migration, which normally sees the mass of red crabs blocking traffic.

title.children: Dry weather delays Christmas Island crab migration

image.altText: A wooden cross sticks up out of green grass, against a blue sky

props.synopsis: Dozens of people have been killed in a clash between tribes in Papua New Guinea's Highlands that's been described as an "ambush".

title.children: At least 49 people have been killed in the largest PNG Highlands 'massacre' in recent history. Here's what we know

image.altText: Woman and dog wrapped in muslin cloth

props.synopsis: Struggling to pay rent in Sydney, Alys McDonough bought what she says was one of the cheapest houses in Australia. She's now back living there, with no mains power and with a bit of ceiling missing, but she says she's sorted.

title.children: Struggling to pay rent, Alys bought a dilapidated house in the outback for about $12,000
